WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:03.150
All right.

00:00:03.150 --> 00:00:03.860
Hi, everybody.

00:00:04.520 --> 00:00:07.000
Welcome to the lightning talk section.

00:00:07.000 --> 00:00:08.440
My name is Jessie.

00:00:08.440 --> 00:00:12.240
I'm going to be giving a quick lightning talk on halluc

00:00:12.240 --> 00:00:17.280
inating the app protocol, grounding your AI agents with the official

00:00:17.280 --> 00:00:18.740
app proto docs.

00:00:18.980 --> 00:00:22.560
If you met me last year, I was at the conference

00:00:22.720 --> 00:00:24.280
talking about OAuth.

00:00:24.280 --> 00:00:28.290
Today I am here because I chose to build and serve for

00:00:28.470 --> 00:00:32.930
free a remote MCP server for the app protocol documentation that

00:00:33.080 --> 00:00:34.470
is available online.

00:00:34.470 --> 00:00:37.670
I'm hoping it is a helpful tool for developers.

00:00:37.670 --> 00:00:42.020
And you may be wondering why would somebody decide to build a

00:00:42.020 --> 00:00:45.860
remote MCP server for the documentation?

00:00:45.950 --> 00:00:49.000
I'm hopefully going to explain.

00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:52.250
So first, if you are not familiar with what RAG

00:00:52.250 --> 00:00:53.890
is, I'm not going to get too deep into this

00:00:53.890 --> 00:00:56.880
because it's a lightning talk, but RAG stands for

00:00:56.880 --> 00:00:59.470
Retrieval Augmented Generation.

00:00:59.590 --> 00:01:03.540
And you can think of retrieval augmented generation as adding index

00:01:03.540 --> 00:01:05.460
ing to your source content.

00:01:05.820 --> 00:01:09.890
So the same way that adding a SQL index to like a

00:01:09.890 --> 00:01:14.550
large SQL table will make querying that data more efficient,

00:01:14.550 --> 00:01:18.240
RAG makes LLM queries more efficient.

00:01:18.240 --> 00:01:21.000
By preprocessing the source content into an index of

00:01:21.020 --> 00:01:24.820
vector embeddings, you get more efficient retrieval of content

00:01:24.820 --> 00:01:27.120
that is specifically related to your query.

00:01:27.170 --> 00:01:31.220
So the way this works is it allows you to combine multiple

00:01:31.220 --> 00:01:34.100
reference sources into a single index.

00:01:34.120 --> 00:01:37.830
You can have that content supersede whatever the model was trained

00:01:37.830 --> 00:01:38.120
on.

00:01:38.120 --> 00:01:41.120
So you can have more up to date, more relevant content

00:01:41.120 --> 00:01:41.360
.

00:01:41.360 --> 00:01:44.320
And then you can also make sure that your retrievals are

00:01:44.720 --> 00:01:46.600
getting grounded in that content.

00:01:46.770 --> 00:01:48.920
So you're reducing hallucinations.

00:01:49.700 --> 00:01:53.000
Quickly, what is an MCP server?

00:01:53.000 --> 00:01:55.930
So if you're not familiar with MCP, it came

00:01:55.930 --> 00:01:57.240
out in late 2024.

00:01:57.240 --> 00:02:01.720
Basically, MCP servers expose tools, prompts, and resources

00:02:01.720 --> 00:02:02.680
to your agents.

00:02:02.680 --> 00:02:05.410
So if you are in Cloud Code or ChatGPT

00:02:05.460 --> 00:02:10.240
or whatever your like tool of choice is, you can often

00:02:10.240 --> 00:02:13.680
install an MCP server that will expose these additional tools,

00:02:14.080 --> 00:02:16.320
prompts, and resources to your queries.

00:02:16.320 --> 00:02:21.240
So let's compare what happens when you do a URL search

00:02:21.240 --> 00:02:25.240
to when you're using something like a a rag instance.

00:02:25.240 --> 00:02:28.630
So if you say, I'm building an app proto app

00:02:28.760 --> 00:02:31.310
, and I want you to search the app proto documentations

00:02:31.310 --> 00:02:34.890
for lexicons, and then you're incorporating that into

00:02:34.890 --> 00:02:35.880
your query.

00:02:35.880 --> 00:02:38.880
Basically, the key point here, you can see this like

00:02:38.880 --> 00:02:40.890
whole little chart of what's happening.

00:02:41.120 --> 00:02:44.140
Your prompt, your agent has to go get the docs,

00:02:44.140 --> 00:02:47.600
it has to tokenize that information, it has to process

00:02:47.600 --> 00:02:48.160
it.

00:02:48.160 --> 00:02:51.890
And basically, the takeaway here is that everything that's going

00:02:51.890 --> 00:02:55.160
into your chat context is getting tokenized and embedded.

00:02:55.160 --> 00:02:57.350
That that could be pre processed.

00:02:57.530 --> 00:03:00.480
And that's what the rag approach allows us to do.

00:03:00.480 --> 00:03:04.850
So instead of your agent tokenizing and embedding all of

00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:09.590
those documentation sources, all of that tokenization and embedding

00:03:09.590 --> 00:03:12.580
vector embedding creation has already happened.

00:03:12.650 --> 00:03:15.200
And it's just being served by the MCP server.

00:03:15.200 --> 00:03:20.280
MCP servers come in two flavors, they come in local

00:03:20.280 --> 00:03:24.070
servers that we run on our local machines and remote servers that

00:03:24.070 --> 00:03:25.840
are hosted somewhere in the cloud.

00:03:25.840 --> 00:03:31.280
By essentially pre processing a rag index and then caching it

00:03:31.280 --> 00:03:33.690
and serving it in the cloud as a remote server, you

00:03:33.690 --> 00:03:37.570
're effectively caching that tokenization process for anyone in the

00:03:37.570 --> 00:03:39.040
world who wants to consume it.

00:03:39.040 --> 00:03:43.760
So this is why I built a app proto docs MCP

00:03:43.760 --> 00:03:44.700
server.

00:03:44.700 --> 00:03:48.400
Last year, when I was first getting into MCP and

00:03:48.400 --> 00:03:52.010
trying to explore it and study it, I thought Cloudfl

00:03:52.310 --> 00:03:55.460
are's documentation server was really interesting to me.

00:03:55.460 --> 00:03:57.790
They had some templates I wanted to clone and see if I

00:03:57.850 --> 00:03:58.720
could play with it.

00:03:58.720 --> 00:04:01.680
This was also in the spirit of we can just build things

00:04:02.080 --> 00:04:02.160
.

00:04:02.160 --> 00:04:07.980
So you can find these online on GitHub at Ember MC

00:04:07.980 --> 00:04:10.220
P app proto docs and the worker.

00:04:10.240 --> 00:04:11.880
How does this actually work?

00:04:12.050 --> 00:04:15.730
There are three pieces to my MCP server that serves the

00:04:16.460 --> 00:04:17.040
documentation.

00:04:17.050 --> 00:04:20.060
There's a cron scraper that actually goes and scrap

00:04:20.260 --> 00:04:23.340
es the documentation sites once a week so that it's kept

00:04:23.340 --> 00:04:25.840
up to date as new documentation is added.

00:04:25.840 --> 00:04:30.640
There's the rag index where a different model preprocess

00:04:30.640 --> 00:04:35.500
es those documentation source sites into a rag index.

00:04:35.500 --> 00:04:39.110
And then there's the actual MCP server itself which exp

00:04:39.110 --> 00:04:42.480
oses that rag index for your agents to query it.

00:04:42.480 --> 00:04:47.470
So the cron scraper it lives at app proto docs

00:04:47.520 --> 00:04:48.080
worker.

00:04:48.080 --> 00:04:52.570
Right now there are only three sources here that are being scra

00:04:52.570 --> 00:04:53.010
ped.

00:04:53.010 --> 00:04:56.640
I'm actually making a list at this conference of sources that

00:04:56.640 --> 00:04:59.010
people want added to this so if you have sources that you

00:04:59.010 --> 00:05:02.270
would like added or feel like should be included please let me

00:05:02.270 --> 00:05:02.810
know.

00:05:02.810 --> 00:05:05.680
You can also open PRs on this public repo.

00:05:05.680 --> 00:05:09.750
Then we have the rag index and I am using a tool

00:05:09.750 --> 00:05:13.280
that Cloudflare has made very affordable right now.

00:05:13.280 --> 00:05:16.680
I don't expect it to stay this affordable forever but right

00:05:16.680 --> 00:05:18.030
now it's lovely.

00:05:18.030 --> 00:05:22.160
And so I am using the open source Quen3 model

00:05:22.160 --> 00:05:25.410
to do the vector embedding that creates the index and that

00:05:25.430 --> 00:05:28.480
's this Cloudflare has some really easy tools that make

00:05:28.480 --> 00:05:30.320
it very simple to do this.

00:05:30.320 --> 00:05:33.440
So that is kind of using some of their stuff.

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:37.410
And then the MCP server itself, mine only exposes

00:05:37.410 --> 00:05:41.040
a single tool and that tool is called search documentation.

00:05:42.480 --> 00:05:46.020
You can make MCP servers as complicated and as interesting as

00:05:46.080 --> 00:05:48.910
you want but mine was just as kind of a prototype so

00:05:48.910 --> 00:05:50.720
it just does search documentation.

00:05:50.720 --> 00:05:55.310
To install this in your agent what you want to do is

00:05:55.310 --> 00:05:59.600
depends on your agent but for example in Cloud you add a

00:05:59.600 --> 00:06:04.300
JSON config which points at the MCP server mine lives at

00:06:04.300 --> 00:06:06.480
this URL.

00:06:06.480 --> 00:06:10.150
And I was not the first nor will I be the last

00:06:10.420 --> 00:06:13.850
person to create an MCP server for at Proto.

00:06:13.850 --> 00:06:17.760
So I wanted to highlight some of the other very awesome MC

00:06:17.820 --> 00:06:20.390
P servers that exist in the community.

00:06:20.390 --> 00:06:22.550
I've added two more since I've been here.

00:06:22.670 --> 00:06:25.030
If you have one that should be on this list, this

00:06:25.030 --> 00:06:27.160
is published as a public gist that I'm going to

00:06:27.520 --> 00:06:29.120
share on Blue Sky after the talk.

00:06:29.320 --> 00:06:31.820
So feel free to tell me about your MCP server and

00:06:31.820 --> 00:06:33.200
I'll make sure it gets included.

00:06:33.200 --> 00:06:36.880
We have mine which is does search documentation.

00:06:36.880 --> 00:06:41.960
We have Lexicon Gardens MCP server which actually serves le

00:06:41.960 --> 00:06:46.680
xicons to and has a describe lexicon as well

00:06:46.680 --> 00:06:52.490
as some authenticated methods where you can actually create and invoke

00:06:52.490 --> 00:06:53.600
XRPC endpoints.

00:06:53.600 --> 00:06:57.790
We have the AshEx has an @proto.

00:06:57.790 --> 00:06:57.960
mcp which is a local documentation MCP server.

00:06:57.960 --> 00:06:58.140
So this is one that you install locally, you run it

00:06:58.140 --> 00:07:00.720
in Python, you perform the RAG indexing locally and

00:07:00.720 --> 00:07:03.180
you have your own local version of that.

00:07:03.180 --> 00:07:03.760
That one actually works off of the GitHub repos as opposed

00:07:03.760 --> 00:07:09.200
to the like HTML content of the doc sites.

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:09.200
We also have some different ones.

00:07:09.200 --> 00:07:13.000
There's Cameron has a very extensive one that actually has a

00:07:13.000 --> 00:07:15.200
disclaimer to not use this as a REST API because it

